pus meum: And they do alow Dunses phantastical ima- ginacion of indiuiduum vagum, that demonstrateth (as he teacheth) in Christes wordes, one thing in substaunce, then beinge (after his mynde) the substaunce of the bodie of Christe.

A marueilous thing howe anye manne can agree with both these two, they beynge soe contrarie the one vnto the other, for the one saieth the woorde (this) demonstrateth the substance of breade, and the other saith ς No, not soe: The breade is gone, and it demonstrateth a substaunce whiche is Christs bodye. Tushe, sayeth thys thyrd man: Ye vnderstand nothing at all, they agree well inough in the chiefe poynte, whiche is the grounde of all, that is boeth doe agree and beare witnesse, that there is transubstancia- tion. They doe agree in deede in that conclusion I graunt, but their profes and doctrine thereof doe euen as well agree together, as dydde the false witnesses before Annas and Caiphas againste Christe, or the two wicked iudges againste Susanna. For againste Christe the false witnesses did agree no (doubte) to speake all againste him: And the wicked iudges were both agreed to condemne poore Susanna, but in examination of their witnesseS, thei dissented so far, that al was found false that they went about, both that wherein they agreed, and also those thinges whiche they brought for their proofes.

Thus muche haue I spoken in searchyng oute a solution for this principall question, which was, what is the mate- riall substaunce of the holy sacramente in the Lordes
